    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-11-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-06-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="115" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d115">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>At its 64th Meeting on August 10, 1950, the National Security Council agreed in
                    principle that the port security program proposed <pb facs="0377" n="361"
                        xml:id="pg_361"/> in document <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 78, August
                    7, 1950 (which concluded that the chief presumed danger of unconventional attack
                    against the harbors, territorial waters, and installations of the United States
                    lay in the uncontrolled use of American ports by Soviet and Soviet satellite
                    vessels), should be put into effect, subject to the working out of details
                    between the departments and agencies concerned. On October 18, 1950, President
                    Truman issued Executive Order 10173 (15 <gloss target="#t_FR1">F.R.</gloss>
                    7005) which instituted a program of port security closely following the
                    recommendations of <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 78. The text of <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 78 and related papers are scheduled for
                    publication in volume IV.</p>
            </div>
